            <p>Published Every Friday.								Telephone&#58; 243&#44; 39th<lb/></p>
            <p>Publication Office<lb/>
                The American Hebrew&#44;<lb/>
                498&#45;500 Third Avenue.<lb/></p>
            <p>New York&#44; March 24th&#44; 1890.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and Dear Sir&#58;&#45;On the 4th of April&#44; we will issue a Passover<lb/> number of the American Hebrew&#44; the distinguishing feature of which<lb/> will be a consensus of opinion on the prejudice against the Jews&#44; partici&#45;<lb/>pated in by the leading Christians of this country&#44; as you will see by<lb/> the enclosed list of contributors.  The enclosed circular and questions<lb/> will give you a better idea of what will appear.  We think that this<lb/> number of The American Hebrew will attract very wide attention<lb/> in the daily and Christian religious press&#44; in a way which cannot<lb/> help having a good effect for our people.  We believe that this issue<lb/> will merit your especial attention in the pulpit during Passover.<lb/>  Should you agree with us&#44; it will afford us pleasure to give you<lb/> an opportunity of seeing the original letters in advance of publication&#44;<lb/> if you happen to be in the city at any time within the next ten<lb/> days&#44; and permit you to make such extracts as you wish for<lb/> your use.<lb/></p>
            <p>It is of course understood that this is written and the enclosed<lb/> matter sent you in confidence&#44; and that you will make no use of<lb/> them until after the appearance of The American Hebrew of April 4th.<lb/>  Sincerely yours&#44;<lb/> Philip Cowen<lb/></p>
            <p>P. S. If more convenient for you&#44; the letters can be seen at my residence&#44;<lb/> 109 E. 65th St.&#44; any evening.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I. Can you&#44; of your own personal experience&#44; find any justification<lb/> whatever for the entertainment of prejudice towards individuals&#44; solely<lb/> because they are Jews&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>II. Is this prejudice not due largely to the religious instruction that<lb/> is given by the Church and Sunday&#45;school&#58;&#45;&#45;for instance&#44; the teachings<lb/> that the Jews crucified Jesus&#59; that they rejected him and can only secure<lb/> salvation by a belief in him&#44; and similar matters that are calculated to<lb/> excite in the impressionable mind of the child an aversion&#44; if not a<lb/> loathing&#44; for members of &#34;the despised race&#63;&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>III. Have you observed in the social and business life of the Jew&#44; so<lb/> far as your personal experience has gone&#44; any different standard of<lb/> conduct than prevails among Christians of the same social status&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>IV. Can you suggest what should be done to dispel the existing<lb/> prejudice&#63;<lb/></p>
                
